Given the constraints you have to follow, I think one option could be to create test-specific implementations that override the `parentAction` to cover the specific use cases.

```kotlin
class ChildTest {

    private Runnable normalAction = Mockito.mock(Runnable.class);
    private Runnable backupAction = Mockito.mock(Runnable.class);

    @Test
    public void shouldUseNormalWhenNoExceptionThrown() {

        Child child = new Child(normalAction, backupAction) {
            @Override
            protected void parentAction() throws Exception {
                System.out.println(&quot;invoked&quot;);
            }
        };
        child.childAction();

        Mockito.verify(normalAction).run();
        Mockito.verify(backupAction, never()).run();
    }

    @Test
    public void shouldUseBackupWhenExceptionThrown() {

        Child child = new Child(normalAction, backupAction) {

            @Override
            public void childAction() {
                super.childAction();
            }

            @Override
            protected void parentAction() throws Exception {
                throw new Exception();
            }
        };
        child.childAction();

        Mockito.verify(backupAction).run();
        Mockito.verify(normalAction, never()).run();
    }
}
```

Please note that this requires changing your `Child` class to avoid calling `super.parentAction()`, but to use just `parentAction()` instead – otherwise it&#39;ll always invoke the method from `Parent` instead of the implementation from the test:

```kotlin
public void childAction() {
    try {
        parentAction();
        this.normalAction.run();
    } catch (Exception e) {
        this.backupAction.run();
    }
}
```

---  

As an alternative, you can use PowerMock to mock the protected method:

```kotlin
@RunWith(PowerMockRunner.class)
@PrepareForTest({Child.class})
class ChildTest {

    private Runnable normalAction = Mockito.mock(Runnable.class);
    private Runnable backupAction = Mockito.mock(Runnable.class);

    @Test
    public void shouldUseNormalWhenNoExceptionThrown() throws Exception {

        Child child = PowerMockito.spy(new Child(normalAction, backupAction));
        PowerMockito.doNothing().when(child, &quot;parentAction&quot;, new Object[] {});

        child.childAction();

        Mockito.verify(normalAction).run();
        Mockito.verify(backupAction, never()).run();
    }

    @Test
    public void shouldUseBackupWhenExceptionThrown() throws Exception {

        Child child = PowerMockito.spy(new Child(normalAction, backupAction));
        doThrow(new Exception()).when(child, &quot;parentAction&quot;);
        child.childAction();

        Mockito.verify(backupAction).run();
        Mockito.verify(normalAction, never()).run();
    }
}
```
However, note that if you&#39;re using JDK17+ you need to specify extra argument to the compiler – see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/69896191/powermock-compatibility-with-jdk-17

